<p><strong>Fill in this Markdown cell with your answers before submitting.</strong></p>
<ol>
<li><p><strong>What was the F1 score of your Logistic Regression baseline?</strong><br>0.6559</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>What was the F1 score of your MLP?</strong><br>0.6559</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Did the MLP outperform the baseline? By how much? Why do you think that is?</strong><br>No. Both models achieved an F1 score of 0.6559, so the improvement was 0.0. This suggests that the MLP failed to learn meaningful patterns from the TF-IDF features, likely because of insufficient training, hyperparameter choices, or an issue in feature generation.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Look at your confusion matrix. Where does your model make the most mistakes - false positives or false negatives? What kind of reviews do you think it gets wrong?</strong><br>  The model appears to predict most reviews as positive. This leads to many false positives and very poor discrimination between positive and negative reviews. Reviews containing mixed sentiment or subtle language are likely being misclassified.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>The model is still using TF-IDF as input. What is the fundamental limitation here? What would need to change to build a truly "understanding" model?</strong><br>TF-IDF represents text as independent word counts and ignores word order, context, and meaning. It cannot understand relationships between words or capture semantic information. To build a truly understanding model, we would need contextual embeddings and sequence models such as transformers or large language models that learn meaning from context.</p>
</li>
</ol>
